<para xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="54" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.s1">
Table 28.2.2 gives the notation for the eigenfunctions corresponding to the eigenvalues in Table 28.2.1.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="55" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.s2">
Period <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.m1">\pi</Math> means that the eigenfunction has the property <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.m2">w(z+\pi)=w(z)</Math> , whereas antiperiod <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.m3">\pi</Math> means that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.m4">w(z+\pi)=-w(z)</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="56" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.s3">
Even parity means <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.m5">w(-z)=w(z)</Math> , and odd parity means <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S2.SS6.p1.m6">w(-z)=-w(z)</Math>.
</sentence>

